t (California politician)|Jack Scott]]\n|birth_name   = Adam Bennett Schiff\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1960|6|22}}\n|birth_place  = [[Framingham, Massachusetts|Framingham]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Eve Sanderson\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Stanford University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Harvard University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website      = {{url|schiff.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Adam Bennett Schiff''' (born June 22, 1960) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|CA|28}}. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], Schiff has served in Congress since 2001. Schiff represented the 27th and 29th Districts between 2001 and 2013, which initially included the areas of [[Alhambra, California|Alhambra]], [[Altadena, California|Altadena]], [[San Gabriel, California|San Gabriel]], [[Burbank, California|Burbank]], [[Glendale, California|Glendale]], [[South Pasadena, California|South Pasadena]], [[Temple City, California|Temple City]], [[Monterey Park, California|Monterey Park]], and [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]]. In 2010, his district's boundaries were re-drawn to include, among others, [[La Ca\u00f1ada Flintridge, California|La Ca\u00f1ada Flintridge]], [[La Crescenta-Montrose, California|La Crescenta-Montrose]] and [[Sunland-Tujunga, Los Angeles|Sunland-Tujunga]], as well as large slices of central [[Los Angeles]] including [[Hollywood, California|Hollywood]], the [[Hollywood Hills, Los Angeles|Hollywood Hills]], [[West Hollywood, California|West Hollywood]], [[Echo Park, Los Angeles|Echo Park]], [[Silver Lake, Los Angeles|Silver Lake]], and [[Los Feliz, Los Angeles|Los Feliz]]. ([[Burbank, California|Burbank]], [[Glendale, California|Glendale]], and the western part of [[Pasadena, California|Pasadena]] all remained in his district.)\n\nSchiff is an influential voice for the Democratic Party on foreign policy and national security issues in the House of Representatives.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Neuman|first1=Johanna|title=Congressman Is Gaining a Name in Foreign Affairs|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/politics/la-me-schiff20jun20-story.html|accessdate=August 22, 2014|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=June 5, 2005}}</ref> He serves as [[ranking member]] of the [[House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]]. He is currently on leave from the [[United States House Committee on Appropriations|House Appropriations Committee]] which he joined in 2007. He previously served on the [[United States House Foreign Affairs Committee]], and serves on the State, Foreign Operations and Related Programs Subcommittee of the Appropriations Committee.\n\n==Early life, education, and career==\nSchiff was born in [[Framingham, Massachusetts]], the son of Edward and Sherrill Ann (Glovsky) Schiff.<ref>Stone, Kurt F. (2011). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=ACTF56SnaykC&pg=PA564 The Jews of Capitol Hill: A Compendium of Jewish Congressional Members]''. Lanham, MD: Scarecrow Press. {{ISBN|9780810857315}}. p. 564.</ref> He was raised in a [[Jewish]] family, and moved to [[Danville, California]], during high school.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Peschiutta|first1=Claudia|title=Meet Adam Schiff|url=http://articles.glendalenewspress.com/2000-07-22/news/export46525_1_adam-schiff-democrats-harvard-law-school|accessdate=August 22, 2014|agency=Glendale News-Press|date=July 22, 2000}}</ref> He received a political science degree from [[Stanford University]] and a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from [[Harvard Law School]].\n\nAfter Harvard Law School, Schiff began working as a prosecutor in the Los Angeles branch of the [[U.S. Attorney's Office]]. While an assistant U.S. Attorney, he gained attention by prosecuting a case against [[Richard Miller (agent)|Richard Miller]], a former FBI agent convicted of \"passing secret documents to the Soviet Union in exchange for a promised $65,000 in gold and cash.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Soble|first1=Ronald|title=Ex-FBI Agent Miller Guilty of Espionage|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1990-10-10/news/mn-1957_1_fbi-agent|accessdate=August 22, 2014|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=October 10, 1990}}</ref> The first time Miller was tried, it resulted in a hung jury; the second time, it resulted in a conviction overturned on appeal,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fleeman|first1=Michael|title=THIRD ESPIONAGE TRIAL BEGINS FOR FORMER FBI AGENT|url=http://www.apnewsarchive.com/1990/Third-Espionage-Trial-Begins-for-Former-FBI-Agent/id-59774f086411dbd2a5adcd1eaa91ce54|accessdate=August 22, 2014|agency=Associated Press|date=August 22, 1990}}</ref> and the third time he was convicted.<ref>{{cite article |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=December 8, 1989 |first=Henry |last=Weinstein |title=Gave Soviets Nothing, Miller Says : Espionage: The former FBI agent says his relationship with a Russian woman spy was 'the dumbest thing I did in my whole life.' |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1989-12-08/local/me-100_1_ex-fbi-agent}}</ref>\n\n==California State Senate==\nSchiff was elected to the [[California State Senate]] in 1996, after two unsuccessful bids for state assembly.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mills|first1=James|title=Adam Schiff Enjoying Getting to Know West Hollywood|url=http://patch.com/california/westhollywood/adam-schiff-enjoying-getting-to-know-west-hollywood|accessdate=August 22, 2014|agency=Patch-AOL|date=August 30, 2012}}</ref>  He chaired that body's judiciary committee during his one term.\n\nAlthough Schiff was elected to [[California's 21st State Senate district]], the area the district currently represents has changed through redistricting, and the area Schiff originally represented is now roughly considered the [[California's 25th State Senate district|25th Senate district]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Halper |first1=Evan |last2=Simon |first2=Richard |title=District maps draw a new political landscape |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/jun/11/local/la-me-new-maps-20110611 |accessdate=July 20, 2018 |publisher=LA Times |date=June 11, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Legislative District Maps |url=http://www.joincalifornia.com/page/8 |website=JoinCalifornia |accessdate=July 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring his tenure in the state senate, Schiff authored Senate Bill 1847, Chapter 1021. Signed into law in 1998, this created the Pasadena Blue Line Authority, which continued work on the stalled then-Blue Line light rail extension to Pasadena, which would later be named the [[Gold Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Gold Line]] instead.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Adam Schiff, Maria Karras, and Heather Podesta.jpg|thumb|Schiff and lobbyist [[Heather Podesta]] at a party hosted by the [[Podesta Group]] in Washington, D.C. in honor of the inauguration of [[Barack Obama]].]]\nSchiff is currently serving his ninth term in Congress.\n\n===2003 invasion of Iraq===\nSchiff voted in favor of the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]].<ref>\"[https://www.nytimes.com/2002/10/10/international/roll-call-vote-in-house-on-iraq-resolution.html Roll Call Vote in House on Iraq Resolution]\". ''[[The New York Times]]''. October 10, 2002.</ref> In February 2015, discussing how or whether to tailor Bush-era plans from 2001 and 2002 to fight ISIS, Schiff was asked if he regretted voting to invade. He said, \"Absolutely. Unfortunately, our intelligence was dead wrong on that, on Saddam at that time. [The vote] set in motion a cascading series of events which have [had] disastrous consequences.\"<ref>[http://www.shafaaq.com/en/En_NewsReader/a968eb27-d910-4b6f-bbac-d4c9506ef639 ''U.S. Deputy: We do not want a second invasion of Iraq and Arabs must end their wars themselves'']. ''SHAFAQ.'' February 13, 2015.</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Obama Asks Congress for War Powers; Interview with Representative Adam Schiff|url=http://www.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1502/11/cnr.01.html|publisher=[[CNN]] |date=February 11, 2015|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Adam Schiff 115th official photo.jpg|thumb|Schiff posing for a picture in the [[United States Capitol]]]]\n[[File:US congressional delegation at HISF 2014.jpg|thumb|US congressional delegation at [[Halifax International Security Forum]] 2014]]\n[[File:Rep. Adam Schiff with Ehud Barak at HISF2014 (15232331943).jpg|thumb|Schiff with former [[Israel]]i Prime Minister [[Ehud Barak]] in November 2014]]\n\n===Armenian genocide resolution===\nSchiff has been a leading voice in [[Armenian-American]] issues; he claims to have over 70,000 Armenian-Americans in his district.<ref>Washington Post: \"Worse than irrelevant: A congressional resolution about massacres in Turkey 90 years ago endangers present-day U.S. security\", p. A16, October 10, 2007</ref><ref>Wall Street Journal: \"Political History\", Review & Outlook, October 2, 2007</ref> He introduced [[United States resolution on Armenian Genocide|U.S. House Resolution 106]], recognizing the [[Armenian genocide]], which was approved by the House Foreign Affairs Committee on October 11, 2007<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.voanews.com/english/2007-10-11-voa71.cfm |title=U.S. House Speaker: Armenian Genocide Measure Will Go Forward |accessdate=October 11, 2007 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013022525/http://www.voanews.com/english/2007-10-11-voa71.cfm |archivedate=October 13, 2007 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> but began to lose support after Turkey's prime minister said that approval of the resolution would endanger U.S.-Turkey relations.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/oilRpt/idUKL1262442020071012 |title=Turkey's PM says U.S. relations in danger |accessdate=October 12, 2007 | work=Reuters | date=October 12, 2007| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20071013151132/http://uk.reuters.com/article/oilRpt/idUKL1262442020071012| archivedate= October 13, 2007 | deadurl= no}}</ref> On March 4, 2010 the resolution was again approved to go forward by the House Foreign Affairs Committee by a 23-22 margin.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-na-armenian-genocide5-2010mar05,0,6057070.story |title=House panel narrowly passes recognition of Armenian genocide |accessdate=March 4, 2010 |work=Los Angeles Times |first1=Richard |last1=Simon |first2=Teresa |last2=Watanabe |date=March 5, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100307033355/http://www.latimes.com/news/nation-and-world/la-na-armenian-genocide5-2010mar05%2C0%2C6057070.story |archivedate=March 7, 2010 |deadurl=no }}</ref> Immediately, the Turkish government recalled its U.S. ambassador.<ref name=latimes/>  Schiff said in 2007, \"When you think about what we have against us -- the president, a foreign policy establishment that has condoned this campaign of denial, the Turkish lobby -- against that you have the truth, which is a powerful thing but doesn't always win out.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Genocide resolution's support starts to fade|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2007/oct/17/nation/na-genocide17|publisher=''[[L.A. Times]]''|author=Simon, Richard|date=October 17, 2007|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> He continues to reintroduce the resolution each subsequent Congress.{{citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\n===Campaign finance reform===\nAfter the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] struck down [[campaign finance reform in the United States|campaign finance reform]] legislation in the [[Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission]] and [[McCutcheon v. Federal Election Commission]] cases, Schiff introduced a constitutional amendment to overturn both decisions, H.J.Res 31, drafted by Harvard Law School Constitutional scholar Laurence H. Tribe.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wells|first1=Jason|title=Rep. Schiff introduces constitutional amendment to overturn Citizens United decision|url=http://articles.glendalenewspress.com/2012-06-18/news/tn-818-0618-rep-schiff-introduces-constitutional-amendment-to-}}{{Dead link|date=August 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Helicopter noise===\nBeginning with Rep. [[Howard Berman]] before Berman was defeated for reelection, Schiff has worked on reducing unwanted helicopter noise across [[Los Angeles County, California|Los Angeles County]] by proposing legislation to force the [[FAA]] to study and regulate helicopter noise in Los Angeles, the Helicopter Noise Relief Act.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Aguilar|first1=Erika|title=Congressman Schiff says he will reintroduce helicopter noise bill|url=http://www.scpr.org/blogs/news/2012/12/07/11459/congressman-schiff-says-he-will-reintroduce-helico/|accessdate=December 9, 2014|agency=Southern California Public Radio|date=December 7, 2012}}</ref> After reintroducing his legislation, Schiff worked with Senator [[Dianne Feinstein]] to push the FAA to act, and together they attached a provision in the 2014 omnibus appropriations package directing the Secretary of the [[Department of Transportation]] and FAA to address helicopter noise in Los Angeles County skies.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Simon|first1=Richard|title=Spending bill to likely give L.A. $130 million for key rail projects|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-transportation-funding-los-angeles-20140114-story.html|accessdate=December 9, 2014|agency=Los Angeles Times|date=January 14, 2014}}</ref> As a result, in 2015 the FAA created a county-wide helicopter noise public complaint system, the first step towards regulation.<ref>{{cite web|title=FAA To Create Public Complaint System For Helicopter Noise|url=http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2014/09/22/faa-to-create-public-complaint-system-for-helicopter-noise/|website=CBS Los Angeles|accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Complaint system for helicopter noise begins operations countywide|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-copter-complaint-system-20150401-story.html|author=Weikel, Dan|publisher=''[[L.A. Times]]''|date=April 1, 2015|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Intelligence and surveillance reform===\nSchiff has been a prominent supporter of surveillance reforms, especially in the wake of the leaks of classified intelligence by [[Edward Snowden]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Holman|first1=Kwame|title=Crusader for More Transparency on Intelligence Sees Risk and Reward From Snowden Leaks|url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/rundown/crusader-for-more-transparency-on-intelligence-sees-risk-and-reward-from-snowden-leaks/|accessdate=December 9, 2014|agency=PBS|date=July 2, 2013}}</ref> In 2007, in response to disclosure of the [[Terrorist Surveillance Program]], Schiff and Rep. [[Jeff Flake]] offered a successful amendment in the House of Representatives to clarify that the [[Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act]] is the exclusive means for collecting foreign intelligence information within the United States.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Nate|title=House reaffirms FISA as \"exclusive means by which electronic surveillance may be conducted\"|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2007/05/house-reaffirms-fisa-as-exclusive-means-by-which-electronic-surveillance-may-be-conducted/|website=Ars Technica|accessdate=December 7, 2014}}</ref> Schiff has been a critic of the bulk collection of telephone metadata by the [[National Security Agency]]. In January 2014, Schiff introduced the Telephone Metadata Reform Act,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Shabad|first1=Rebecca|title=Schiff unveils NSA metadata reform bill|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/195381-schiff-unveils-nsa-metadata-reform-bill|accessdate=December 7, 2014|agency=The Hill|date=January 14, 2014}}</ref> which would prohibit the bulk collection of domestic phone records. Schiff has also introduced several bills aimed at reforming the [[Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Court]], including a bill to require outside counsel to be appointed to argue for privacy and civil liberties protections in certain cases before the Court.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Sledge|first1=Matt|title=Adam Schiff Prepares FISA Court Bill To Create Special Privacy Advocate|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/07/25/adam-schiff-fisa-court_n_3653946.html|website=The Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\n===Investigation of Benghazi attack===\nSchiff was appointed to the [[United States House Select Committee on Events Surrounding the 2012 Terrorist Attack in Benghazi|House Select Committee on Benghazi]] in 2014 by [[Nancy Pelosi]] to serve as one of the five Democrats on the Committee.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Weisman|first1=Jonathan|title=Pelosi Picks 5 Democrats for Panel on Benghazi|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/05/22/us/politics/bucking-deputies-pelosi-picks-5-democrats-for-benghazi-panel.html?_r=0|accessdate=August 23, 2014|agency=New York Times|date=May 22, 2014}}</ref> Schiff had participated in the [[House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]] investigation into the attacks on the Benghazi diplomatic compound, which found that the initial talking points provided by the intelligence community were flawed but without an intention to deceive, and that diplomatic facilities across the world lacked adequate security.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Dierdre|title=Benghazi probe presses ahead despite new report|url=http://www.cnn.com/2014/08/06/politics/benghazi-select-committee/index.html|accessdate=August 23, 2014|date=August 6, 2014}}</ref> The report's findings were unanimous and bipartisan. Before he was appointed as a Member of the Benghazi Select Committee, Schiff called the establishment of a select committee to investigate the 2012 attack a \"colossal waste of time,\" and said Democratic leaders should not appoint any members, stating: \"I think it's just a tremendous red herring and a waste of taxpayer resources.\"<ref name=Hicks>{{cite news|last=Hicks|first=Josh|title=Schiff: Benghazi select committee a \u2018colossal waste of time\u2019|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2014/05/04/schiff-benghazi-select-committee-a-colossal-waste-of-time/|accessdate=May 10, 2014|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=May 4, 2014}}</ref> Despite those reservations, he still accepted an appointment to the Committee because if he felt he \"could add value, [he] would serve.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mikailian|first1=Arin|title=House appoints Schiff to Benghazi investigation committee|url=http://www.burbankleader.com/news/tn-blr-house-appoints-schiff-to-benghazi-investigation-committee-20140524,0,7139046.story|accessdate=August 23, 2014|agency=Burbank Leader|date=May 24, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Press freedom===\nSchiff formed the bipartisan, bicameral Congressional Caucus for the Freedom of the Press in 2006<ref>{{cite web|title=The Congressional Caucus for Freedom of the Press Calls on Secretary of State Rice to Urge Russia to Protect Journalist Rights|url=http://schiff.house.gov/s2006/the-congressional-caucus-for-freedom-of-the-press-calls-on-secretary-of-state-rice-to-urge-russia-to-protect-journalist-rights/|website=Schiff Congressional Website|accessdate=December 9, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141207013721/https://schiff.house.gov/s2006/the-congressional-caucus-for-freedom-of-the-press-calls-on-secretary-of-state-rice-to-urge-russia-to-protect-journalist-rights/|archive-date=December 7, 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref> aimed at advancing press freedom around the world.  The Caucus proposed the [[Daniel Pearl Freedom of the Press Act]] and it was originally introduced to Congress by Schiff and Rep. [[Mike Pence]] (R., Ind.) and by Sen. [[Christopher Dodd]] (D., Conn.) on October 1, 2009 in response to the murder of [[Daniel Pearl]] by terrorists in Pakistan.<ref name=CypressTimes>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecypresstimes.com/article/News/National_News/PRESIDENT_OBAMA_SIGNS_THE_DANIEL_PEARL_FREEDOM_OF_THE_PRESS_ACT/30207|title=President Obama Signs the Daniel Pearl Freedom of the Press Act|work=The Cypress Times|accessdate=December 1, 2010}}</ref><ref name=WallStJournal>{{cite news|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/05/17/obama-signs-daniel-pearl-press-freedom-act/|title=Obama Signs Pearl Press-Freedom Act|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=December 1, 2010|first=Laura|last=Meckler|date=May 17, 2010}}</ref> The legislation requires the [[United States Department of State]] to expand its scrutiny of [[news media]] [[intimidation]] and [[freedom of the press]] restrictions during its annual report on [[human rights]] in each country.<ref name=NYTimes>{{cite news|title=U.S. to Promote Press Freedom |newspaper=The New York Times |location=New York, NY}}</ref> After its introduction, the act passed through the [[United States House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] with a vote of 403 to 12 and passed unanimously in the [[United States Senate|Senate]]; however, a provision requiring the Secretary of State (in coordination with the Department of State\u2019s Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor, and in consultation with the Undersecretary for Public Affairs and Public Diplomacy) to establish a grant program aiming to promote freedom of the press worldwide was removed in the Senate.<ref name=WallStJournal/><ref>Liberman, Rachel (May 18, 2010). \"[http://www.sociologylens.net/topics/communication-and-media/the-daniel-pearl-freedom-of-the-press-act-a-positive-step-in-an-ambiguous-direction/6480 The Daniel Pearl Freedom of the Press Act: A positive step in an ambiguous direction]\". ''Sociology Lens''. sociology.net. Retrieved June 2, 2017.</ref> On May 17, 2010 President Barack Obama, accompanied by the Pearl family, signed into law the Daniel Pearl Freedom of the Press Act.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Meckler|first1=Laura|title=Obama Signs Daniel Pearl Press Freedom Act|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2010/05/17/obama-signs-daniel-pearl-press-freedom-act/|accessdate=December 9, 2014|agency=Wall Street Journal|date=May 17, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen===\nIn 2015, Schiff supported the [[Saudi Arabian-led intervention in Yemen]], saying: \"The military action by Saudi Arabia and its partners was necessitated by the illegal action of the Houthi rebels and their Iranian backers. ... But ultimately, a negotiated end to this crisis is the only way to restore order in Yemen and shrink the space for terrorism.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2015/03/27/saudi-arabia-gets-bipartisan-backing-for-yemen-airstrikes |title=Saudi Arabia Gets Bipartisan Backing for Yemen Airstrikes |work=U.S. News. |date=March 27, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328004338/http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2015/03/27/saudi-arabia-gets-bipartisan-backing-for-yemen-airstrikes |archivedate=March 28, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===War authorization reform and authorization against ISIS===\nAfter the President's speech at the [[National Defense University]] examining the U.S. war powers during the [[War on Terror]], Schiff introduced bipartisan legislation to repeal the 2001 [[Authorization for Use of Military Force Against Terrorists]], the legislation passed in the days after the [[September 11 attacks]] to combat [[Al Qaeda]], because he felt that \"the current AUMF is outdated and straining at the edges to justify the use of force outside the war theater.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Ackerman|first1=Spencer|title=Congressman Preps Bill to End Terror War Authority|url=https://www.wired.com/2013/05/schiff-aumf/|website=Wired|accessdate=December 9, 2014}}</ref> The bill, introduced with Rep. [[Tom Rooney (politician)|Tom Rooney]] (R-FL), was intended to sunset.  In addition to his legislation, Schiff has been a forceful proponent of debating and voting on a new war authorization against [[ISIS]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Schiff|first1=Adam|title=Congress must exercise its war powers|url=http://www.latimes.com/opinion/op-ed/la-oe-1118-schiff-islamic-state-congress-vote-20141114-story.html|accessdate= December 9, 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|date= November 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Comments on Trump-Russia collusion investigation===\n{{further|Special Counsel investigation (2017\u2013present)}}\n\nOn April 2, 2017 Schiff, the [[ranking member]] on the [[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|House Select Intelligence Committee]] which is tasked with conducting inquiries related to [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections]], appeared on [[CNN]]'s ''[[State of the Union]]''. In the wide-ranging interview Schiff and host [[Jake Tapper]] discussed [[Michael Flynn]]'s request for immunity, Schiff's and [[Devin Nunes]]'s separate inspections of White House documents, Trump's allegations of wiretapping in Trump Tower, and Nunes's apparent close association with the Trump White House.<ref>{{cite news|title=Top Democrat accuses White House of trying to distract from Russia probe|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-trump-russia-probe-20170402-story.html|author=Parker, Ashley|date=April 2, 2017 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Tapper asked Schiff if there was evidence of [[Donald Trump]]\u2013[[Russia]] collusion. Schiff replied: \"I don't think we can say anything definitively at this point. We are still at the very early stage of the investigation. The only thing I can say is that it would be irresponsible for us not to get to the bottom of this.\"<ref>\"[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/04/02/schiff-still-no-definitive-link-between-russia-trump-campaign.html Schiff: Still no 'definitive' link between Russia, Trump campaign]\". ''Fox News.'' April 2, 2017.</ref> Tapper asked, \"Do you think that Chairman [[Devin Nunes|Nunes]] was part of an attempt to provide some sort of cover for the president's claim about Obama wiretapping him at [[Trump Tower]], which, obviously, this does not prove, but to cover for that, or an attempt to distract, as you're suggesting?\" Schiff replied, \"It certainly is an attempt to distract and to hide the origin of the materials, to hide the White House hand. The question is, of course, why? And I think the answer to the question is this effort to point the Congress in other directions, basically say, don't look at me, don't look at Russia, there is nothing to see here.\"<ref>{{cite news|title= Interview With California Congressman Adam Schiff|url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1704/02/sotu.01.html|publisher=[[CNN]]|date=April 2, 2017|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> \nA few days later Nunes recused himself as leader of the investigative panel while the [[United States House Committee on Ethics|House Committee on Ethics]] investigated whether he had disclosed classified information.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Swift Fall of Devin Nunes|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/04/the-swift-fall-of-devin-nunes/522144/|author=Berman, Russell|date=April 6, 2017|publisher==''[[The Atlantic]]''|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Devin Nunes to Step Aside From House Investigation on Russia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/04/06/us/politics/devin-nunes-house-intelligence-committee-russia.html|author=Huetteman, Emmarie|date=April 6, 2017|publisher=''[[The New York Times]]''|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn July 23, 2017, on \"[[Meet the Press]]\", Schiff stated, \"[A]t the end of the day we need to make sure that our president is operating not in his personal best interests and not because he's worried about what the Russians might have but because what he is doing is in America's best interest. The fact that we have questions about this is in itself harmful.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/transcript-rep-adam-schiff-on-face-the-nation-july-23-2017/|title=Transcript: Rep. Adam Schiff on \"Face the Nation,\" July 23, 2017|access-date=July 24, 2017|language=en}}</ref>  The following morning on Twitter President Trump referred to Schiff as \"Sleazy Adam Schiff, the totally biased Congressman looking into 'Russia'\" and called the Russian collusion investigation \"the Dem loss excuse\".<ref>{{cite news|title=California's Rep. Adam Schiff gets a Trump nickname: 'Sleazy'|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/essential/la-pol-ca-essential-politics-updates-trump-calls-california-rep-schiff-1500907078-htmlstory.html|author=Wire, Sarah D.|date=July 24, 2017|publisher=''[[L.A. Times]]''|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Schiff responded on Twitter that the President's \"comments and actions are beneath the dignity of the office.\"<ref>{{cite tweet |user=RepAdamSchiff |number=889484105833959430|title=With respect Mr. President, the problem is how often you watch TV|date=July 24, 2017|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===North Korea===\nSchiff called [[North Korea]] \"one of the most brutal and despotic regimes in the world.\" After the death of American student [[Otto Warmbier]] who had been imprisoned during a visit to North Korea, Schiff said: \"The barbaric treatment of Otto Warmbier by the North Korean regime amounts to the murder of a U.S. citizen.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=After Otto Warmbier's death, top senators say U.S. should consider banning North Korea travel |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2017/06/20/otto-warmbier-death-senators-north-korea-travel/412477001/ |work=USA Today |date=June 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Schiff said President Trump deserved credit for bringing North Korea to the [[2018 North Korea\u2013United States summit|negotiating table]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Trump's 'Unpredictability' Helped North Korea Peace Talks, Adam Schiff Says |url=http://www.newsweek.com/trumps-unpredictability-helped-north-korea-table-adam-schiff-says-905342 |work=Newsweek |date=April 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Committee and caucuses==\n===Committee assignments===\n*'''[[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence (Ranking Member)]]'''\n*'''[[United States House Select Committee on Events Surrounding the 2012 Terrorist Attack in Benghazi|House Select Committee on Benghazi]]'''\n\n===Caucuses===\n*Co-chair of the Congressional International Anti-Piracy Caucus\n*Co-founded the Democratic Study Group on National Security\n*Co-founded the Congressional Caucus for Freedom of the Press\n*Vice Chair of the Congressional LGBT Equality Caucus<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|url=https://lgbt-polis.house.gov/members|website=Congressional LGBT Equality Caucus|accessdate=August 31, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n*'''[[New Democrat Coalition]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://newdemocratcoalition-himes.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=New Democrat Coalition|date=|accessdate=February 6, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[House Baltic Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://housebalticcaucus.webs.com/members|format=|publisher=House Baltic Caucus|date=|accessdate=February 21, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Afterschool Caucuses]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.afterschoolalliance.org/policyCongressionalCaucuses.cfm|format=|publisher=Afterschool Alliance|date=|accessdate=April 17, 2018}}</ref>\n*'''[[Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus]]'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=https://capac-chu.house.gov/members|format=|publisher=Congressional Asian Pacific American Caucus|date=|accessdate=May 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Congressional campaigns==\nIn 2000, Schiff challenged Republican incumbent [[Jim Rogan]] in what was then the 27th District.  The district had once been a Republican stronghold, but had been trending Democratic since the early 1990s.  In what was the most expensive House race ever at the time<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opensecrets.org/bigpicture/topraces.php?cycle=2000&Display=allcands |title=Most Expensive Races 2000 |author=Center for Responsive Politics |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> (several elections in 2006<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opensecrets.org/bigpicture/topraces.php?cycle=2006&Display=allcands |title=Most Expensive Races 2006 |author=Center for Responsive Politics |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> and 2008<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.opensecrets.org/bigpicture/topraces.php?cycle=2008&Display=allcands |title=Most Expensive Races 2008 |author=Center for Responsive Politics |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> later eclipsed it), Schiff unseated Rogan, taking 53 percent of the vote to Rogan's 44 percent.  He became only the second Democrat to represent this district since its creation in 1913.\n\nAfter the 2000 census, the district was renumbered as the 29th and made significantly more Democratic.  As a result, Schiff has never faced another contest nearly as close as his 2000 bid, and has been reelected eight times.  His district became even more Democratic after the 2010 census, when it was renumbered as the 28th and pushed into Los Angeles itself.\n\nIn 2010, Schiff defeated Tea Party\u2013backed Republican John Colbert for a sixth term.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Schiff wins big in bid to return to Congress |url=http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/news/ci_16512974 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120313184506/http://www.pasadenastarnews.com/news/ci_16512974 |archive-date=March 13, 2012 }}</ref>{{dead link|date=July 2018}} In 2012, he defeated Republican Phil Jennerjahn.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.glendalenewspress.com/2012-11-07/news/tn-gnp-1107-gatto-liu-schiff-handily-hold-on-to-their-seats_1_phil-jennerjahn-schiff-carol-liu |title=Gatto, Liu, Schiff handily hold on to their seats |authors=Jason Wells and Mark Kellam |date=November 7, 2012 |work=[[Glendale News-Press]] |location=Glendale, California |access-date=February 13, 2017}}</ref>  In 2014, he defeated independent candidate Steve Stokes.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kellam|first1=Mark|title=Schiff, Gatto easily win their political races|url=http://www.glendalenewspress.com/news/tn-gnp-me-schiff-gatto-have-easy-wins-in-their-political-races-20141105,0,1749310.story|accessdate=November 21, 2014 |work=[[Glendale News-Press]] }}</ref> In 2016, he defeated Republican candidate Lenore Solis.\n\n==Personal life==\nSchiff and his wife Eve have two children, Alexa and Elijah.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://adamschiff.com/meet-adam/ |title=About Adam Schiff for Congress |publisher=AdamSchiff.com |accessdate=May 27, 2018}}</ref>\n\nSchiff has participated in multiple endurance challenges including triathlons and marathons. Schiff was the only Congressman to participate in the inaugural Washington, D.C. triathlon in 2010,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilkie|first1=Christina|title=Schiff completes inaugural D.C. Triathlon|url=http://articles.glendalenewspress.com/2010-07-01/news/tn-gnp-pollandscape-20100701_1_rep-adam-schiff-triathlon-financial-firms|accessdate=August 22, 2014|date=June 21, 2010}}</ref> and has since participated in other races in Philadelphia, New York City and Malibu.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rojas|first1=Warren|title=Adam Schiff Mounts Most Grueling Endurance Challenge Yet|url=http://hoh.rollcall.com/adam-schiff-to-ride-from-san-francisco-to-los-angeles/|accessdate=August 22, 2014|agency=Roll Call|date=May 30, 2014}}</ref>  In 2014, Schiff was the first member of Congress to participate in the [[AIDS/LifeCycle]], a seven-day charity bike ride from San Francisco to Los Angeles to raise awareness and funding to fight [[HIV]] and [[AIDS]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=St. John|first1=Stevie|title=Rep. Schiff Pedaling from SF to LA with HIV/AIDS Ride|url=http://www.wehoville.com/2014/05/31/congressman-adam-schiff-pedaling-sf-l-aidslifecycle-hivaids-ride/|accessdate=August 22, 2014|agency=WEHOville|date=May 31, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{wikisource autho